SIMPLE: fluent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fluent
<hw>Flu"ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>fluens</ets>,
<ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>fluere</ets> to flow; cf. Gr. <?/ to
boil over. Cf. <er>Fluctuate</er>, <er>Flux</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Flowing or capable of flowing; liquid; glodding; easily
moving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Ready in the use of words; voluble; copious; having
words at command; and uttering them with facility and smoothness;
<as>as, a <ex>fluent</ex> speaker</as>; hence, flowing; voluble; smooth;
-- said of language; <as>as, <ex>fluent</ex> speech</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With most <qex>fluent</qex> utterance.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fluent</qex> as the flight of a swallow is the sultan's
letter.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fluent
<hw>Flu"ent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A current of water; a
stream.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>fluente</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A variable quantity, considered as increasing or
diminishing; -- called, in the modern calculus, the
<altname>function</altname> or <altname>integral</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluently</ent>⟦br⟧
